result.execSummary:
The defendant Kaylynn M Ording was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (5th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: Bond amount posted shall be applied and balance shall be applied to 14CF216.  Outstanding financial obligations shall be paid from all prison wages at a rate of 25% and the balance due as a condition of extended supervision.  If extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with financial obligations owing, a judgment shall be entered.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment and stable residence.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant shall not possess any alcohol or controlled substance without a valid prescription and then take medication as prescribed.

Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle without a valid license or proof of insurance.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent and comply with recommendations.

Defendant shall pay any supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA assessment and comply with recommendations.
